# Dasco Pro 408 3/4" Cold Chisel

**American-made workhorse. Compact, tough, and precise — a solid addition to any electrician’s or contractor’s tool inventory.**

## Specifications
- **Blade Width**: 3/4 inch  
- **Overall Length**: 7-1/8 inches  
- **Material**: High-carbon steel, heat-treated  
- **Edge**: Precision ground  
- **Country of Origin**: USA  

## Pros
- Excellent edge retention and toughness for daily jobsite use  
- Compact size provides superior control in tight spaces  
- Precision-ground tip shears cleanly on metal  
- Reliable American-made quality you can feel  

## Cons
- No hand guard — keep fingers clear when hammering  
- Striking end will mushroom over time (dress it regularly)  
- Not ideal for heavy concrete or masonry work  

## Best Use Cases
- Cutting off stubborn conduit straps and rusted hardware  
- Cleaning high spots in concrete for box or equipment installs  
- Shearing bolts, rivets, or welded tabs during demolition  
- Fleet maintenance — splitting frozen nuts, removing burrs, general metal cleanup  
- Controlled cutting of copper, bronze, steel, and cast iron  

## Similar Tools
- Dasco larger cold chisels (e.g., G410 series)  
- Klein Tools cold chisels (popular with electricians)  
- Mayhew, Proto, or SK (premium options)  
- Dasco 3-piece cold chisel set (Model 44)  

## Maintenance & Care
- Sharpen cutting edge with a file or bench grinder (avoid overheating)  
- Dress the struck end regularly to prevent mushrooming  
- Wipe with light oil after use  
- Store with tip protected  

## Field Notes
Always use a ball-peen or mason’s hammer. Wear eye protection and gloves. Strike square and follow through. This compact chisel excels where control matters more than brute force.

